==English==
===Etymology===
1711, from Malay kichap, from Chinese [[Min Nan]] ([[鮭]][[汁]], [[wikipedia:POJ|POJ]]: kê-chiap) "brine of fish." Catsup (earlier catchup) is a failed attempt at Anglicization, still in use in U.S. Originally a fish sauce, early English recipes included among their ingredients mushrooms, walnuts, cucumbers, and oysters. Modern form of the sauce began to emerge when U.S. seamen added tomatoes.

===Noun===
{{en-noun-unc}}
{{wikipedia}}

# A tomato-vinegar based [[sauce]]. (The term is now used almost exclusively to refer to ''tomato'' ketchup, however, at one time it was a more general term for sauce and is still occasionally used in this way, such as grape-ketchup.)

